Document: Complex Shapes with Particles
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/particles/complex_shapes.rst
Summary: Explains how particle emission points are affected by the particle system's position and the need to regenerate them when moving the system or source mesh.

The emission points are stored in the particle system's local coordinate system, so you can move the particle node around and the emission points will follow. This might be useful when you want to use the same particle system in several different places. On the other hand, you might have to regenerate the emission points when you move either the particle system or the source mesh.
---CHUNK---
Document: Complex Shapes
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/particles/complex_shapes.rst
Summary: How emission shape textures define particle distribution and properties in Godot's particle system

Emission shape textures store data for complex particle emission patterns. The number of required textures depends on the selected emission shape type. When using the "Points" shape, two textures are needed: Point Texture and Color Texture. For "Directed Points", a third Normal Texture is added.

The Point Texture contains all possible emission points generated in the previous step. Each particle selects a random point from this texture at spawn time. If present, the Normal Texture provides direction vectors at the same locations. The Color Texture, when set, supplies particle colors sampled at the same positions as the other textures, modulating any base color defined in the process material.

The Point Count property allows dynamic adjustment of emission points at any time, including during runtime. This value controls how many points are actively used from the Point Texture for particle spawning.